# Async/Await vs Promises in JavaScript

Great question! Both async/await and Promises handle asynchronous operations, but they offer different syntax approaches. Let me break this down:

## **Promises** - The Foundation
Promises are objects representing eventual completion of async operations:

```javascript
// Promise chain
fetchUser(123)
  .then(user => fetchUserPosts(user.id))
  .then(posts => console.log(posts))
  .catch(error => console.error(error));
```

## **Async/Await** - Cleaner Syntax
Async/await is syntactic sugar over Promises, making async code look synchronous:

```javascript
// Same operation with async/await
async function getUserPosts(userId) {
  try {
    const user = await fetchUser(userId);
    const posts = await fetchUserPosts(user.id);
    console.log(posts);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
}
```

## **When to Use Each:**

**Use Promises when:**
- You need concurrent operations (`Promise.all`, `Promise.race`)
- Working with existing Promise-based libraries
- Simple one-off async operations

**Use Async/Await when:**
- Sequential async operations
- Complex error handling
- You want more readable, "synchronous-looking" code

Remember: async functions always return Promises under the hood!

