# Express.js Routing and Middleware

Great question! Express.js routing and middleware are fundamental concepts that work together to handle HTTP requests. Let me break this down for you:

## Basic Routing

Routing determines how your app responds to client requests to specific endpoints:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Basic routes
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello World!');
});

app.post('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Create a new user');
});

app.put('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  res.send(`Update user ${req.params.id}`);
});
```

## Middleware Functions

Middleware functions execute during the request-response cycle and can:
- Execute code
- Modify request/response objects
- End the request-response cycle
- Call the next middleware function

```javascript
// Application-level middleware
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  console.log('Time:', Date.now());
  next(); // Important: call next() to continue
});

// Route-specific middleware
app.get('/protected', authenticateUser, (req, res) => {
  res.send('Protected content');
});

function authenticateUser(req, res, next) {
  // Check authentication logic here
  if (req.headers.authorization) {
    next(); // Continue to route handler
  } else {
    res.status(401).send('Unauthorized');
  }
}
```

## Router Module

For better organization, use Express Router:

```javascript
// routes/users.js
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();

router.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Users list');
});

router.get('/:id', (req, res) => {
  res.send(`User ${req.params.id}`);
});

module.exports = router;

// In your main app.js
const userRoutes = require('./routes/users');
app.use('/users', userRoutes);
```

