# Media Queries for Responsive Design

Media queries are CSS rules that allow you to apply different styles based on device characteristics like screen width, height, or orientation. They're essential for creating websites that look great on everything from phones to desktop monitors!

## Basic Syntax
```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  /* Styles for screens 768px and smaller */
  .container {
    width: 100%;
    padding: 10px;
  }
}
```

## Common Breakpoints
- **Mobile**: `max-width: 480px`
- **Tablet**: `max-width: 768px`
- **Desktop**: `min-width: 1024px`

## Practical Example
```css
/* Default styles (desktop-first approach) */
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  gap: 20px;
}

/* Tablet */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 15px;
  }
}

/* Mobile */
@media (max-width: 480px) {
  .grid {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 10px;
  }
}
```

## Pro Tips
- Use `em` or `rem` units for breakpoints instead of pixels for better accessibility
- Test on real devices, not just browser dev tools
- Consider touch-friendly button sizes (44px minimum)

