# Replace Conditional with Polymorphism

Great question! This is one of my favorite refactoring techniques. **Replace Conditional with Polymorphism** helps eliminate complex if-else chains by using object-oriented principles.

## The Problem
When you have code like this:
```java
if (type == "CREDIT_CARD") {
    return processCreditCard(amount);
} else if (type == "PAYPAL") {
    return processPayPal(amount);
} else if (type == "BANK_TRANSFER") {
    return processBankTransfer(amount);
}
```

## The Solution
Create a hierarchy of classes that share a common interface:

```java
// Base interface/abstract class
abstract class PaymentProcessor {
    abstract Money process(Money amount);
}

// Concrete implementations
class CreditCardProcessor extends PaymentProcessor {
    Money process(Money amount) {
        // Credit card logic here
    }
}

class PayPalProcessor extends PaymentProcessor {
    Money process(Money amount) {
        // PayPal logic here
    }
}
```

## Benefits
- **Eliminates complex conditionals**
- **Easier to add new types** (just create a new class)
- **Better separation of concerns**
- **More testable code**

