# Error Handling Boilerplate for REST API

Absolutely! Here's a comprehensive error handling setup that I'd recommend for a REST API:

## Custom Error Classes

```javascript
// Custom error classes
class APIError extends Error {
  constructor(message, statusCode = 500, code = 'INTERNAL_ERROR') {
    super(message);
    this.statusCode = statusCode;
    this.code = code;
    this.timestamp = new Date().toISOString();
  }
}

class ValidationError extends APIError {
  constructor(message, field = null) {
    super(message, 400, 'VALIDATION_ERROR');
    this.field = field;
  }
}

class NotFoundError extends APIError {
  constructor(resource) {
    super(`${resource} not found`, 404, 'NOT_FOUND');
  }
}
```

## Global Error Handler Middleware

```javascript
// Express.js error handling middleware
const errorHandler = (err, req, res, next) => {
  // Log the error
  console.error('API Error:', {
    message: err.message,
    stack: err.stack,
    url: req.url,
    method: req.method,
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString()
  });

  // Handle known errors
  if (err instanceof APIError) {
    return res.status(err.statusCode).json({
      success: false,
      error: {
        code: err.code,
        message: err.message,
        timestamp: err.timestamp,
        ...(err.field && { field: err.field })
      }
    });
  }

  // Handle validation errors (e.g., from express-validator)
  if (err.name === 'ValidationError') {
    return res.status(400).json({
      success: false,
      error: {
        code: 'VALIDATION_ERROR',
        message: 'Invalid input data',
        details: err.errors
      }
    });
  }

  // Default error response
  res.status(500).json({
    success: false,
    error: {
      code: 'INTERNAL_ERROR',
      message: 'An unexpected error occurred'
    }
  });
};
```

## Try-Catch Wrapper

```javascript
// Async error wrapper to avoid repeating try-catch
const asyncHandler = (fn) => (req, res, next) => {
  Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);
};

// Usage example
app.get('/users/:id', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  const user = await User.findById(req.params.id);
  if (!user) {
    throw new NotFoundError('User');
  }
  res.json({ success: true, data: user });
}));
```

This setup gives you:
- **Consistent error responses** across your API
- **Proper HTTP status codes**
- **Detailed logging** for debugging
- **Clean controller code** without repetitive error handling

